<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 93 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALUMINIUM prices lost earlier gains yesterday afternoon as lingering concern
over production at the former Soviet Union's Sayansk smelter faded. The
market settled back into its previous restricted range with final London
Metal Exchange business at an unchanged Dollars 1,219 a tonne for three
months delivery. The TIN market seemed to be heading for a test of recent
20-year lows as the three months position closed Dollars 17.50 down at
Dollars 4,917.50 a tonne. NICKEL prices consolidated in the afternoon,
having earlier run into some overhead selling at Dollars 5,050 a tonne for
the three months position. But dealers thought the technical recovery might
yet run further towards the Dollars 5,200-a-tonne level. At the London
bullion market GOLD and SILVER prices ended little changed but the PLATINUM
price firmed another Dollars 2.65 to Dollars 409.25 a troy ounce. Traders
attributed the continued rise in platinum group metal prices to
follow-through from Wednesday's strong performance, during which October
platinum futures in the New York market forged through various resistance
levels ranging from Dollars 411.00 to Dollars 415.00 an ounce.
Compiled from Reuters
</TEXT>
