FT  30 JUL 93 / International Company News: Placer Dome downturn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PLACER DOME, one of Canada's two top gold producers, has reported lower
second-quarter earnings because of a decline in gold production and lower
realised prices.
The June quarter's sales dipped 10 per cent to USDollars 234m, reflecting an
8 per cent fall in gold sales volume and lower realised prices for gold,
copper and molybdenum.
Net profit, including investment income, amounted to USDollars 21m, or 8
cents a share, down from Dollars 24m, or 10 cents, a year earlier.
Gold output totalled 453,000 oz, against 505,000 oz, and the average cash
cost of production was up slightly to Dollars 191 per ounce.
First-half profit was USDollars 32m, or 13 cents a share, against Dollars
35m, or 15 cents, after special gains of Dollars 13m, against Dollars 7m.
Sales revenues were Dollars 447m, against Dollars 507m.
Gold output was 903,000 oz, a fall of 6 per cent, while cash cost of
production was slightly lower.
