<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 93 / International Company News: RJR Nabisco earnings hit by US
cigarette price war
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RJR NABISCO, the large US food and tobacco group, yesterday announced an 11
per cent decline in second-quarter net income to Dollars 77m as a fierce
cigarette price war in the US continued to take its toll on earnings.
Mr Charles Harper, chairman and chief executive, said: 'The extremely
competitive domestic tobacco environment led to a significant decline in our
earnings.'
Annually, RJR's US cigarette business accounts for more than half group
operating profits.
The price war began in April when Philip Morris, RJR's biggest US rival, cut
the prices of its flagship Marlboro brand in an attempt to halt the growing
popularity of discount brands. Later in the same month, RJR announced it was
lowering prices of its top Winston and Camel brands.
Mr Harper issued a warning yesterday about the group's earnings prospects,
saying that RJR expected to incur 'significant expenses' as it adjusted to
the changing business environment.
'Those expenses, along with lower domestic tobacco revenues, will further
depress our financial results through year-end,' he said.
The warning, and the lower profits, hit RJR's shares, which closed Dollars
1/8 lower at Dollars 5 1/8 (a 52-week low) on the New York Stock Exchange.
RJR's second-quarter profits would have been higher but for an after-tax
charge of Dollars 65m related to the repurchase and retirement of debt.
RJR's results in the same quarter a year ago were affected by a charge.
Excluding the special items, RJR's earnings in the latest quarter were 32
per cent lower than in the same three months of 1992.
Operating income in the quarter fell 24 per cent to Dollars 582m, and net
sales dropped 7 per cent to Dollars 3.72bn.
Net Sales in RJR's worldwide tobacco business fell 13 per cent to Dollars
2.03bn following a 20 per cent drop in domestic sales.
The company said, however, that the recent price cuts and increased
promotional activities should lead to improved sales of its top brands.
The food businesses reported a modest improvement in second-quarter sales to
Dollars 1.69bn, a performance that the company said reflected stronger US
and international biscuit volumes, costs savings from productivity
initiatives and the contribution of recent acquisitions.
The news of RJR's falling profits comes a month after the group abandoned
plans to raise Dollars 1.5bn through an offering of shares pegged to the
performance of its food division because of a general weakness in the market
for food company shares.
</TEXT>
<XX>
