<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 93 / Allied to acquire Augustus Barnett
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP RAWSTORNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BASS, the UK's biggest brewer, yesterday confirmed that it is negotiating
the sale of its Augustus Barnett off-licence chain to Allied-Lyons, the
food, drinks and retailing group.
The long-rumoured deal, worth about Pounds 40m according to industry
estimates, would consolidate Allied's position as the country's
second-largest specialist drinks retailer, combining its 970 Victoria Wine
outlets with Augustus Barnett's 540 shops.
Whitbread's Thresher chain, boosted by the Pounds 49.5m acquisition of 667
Peter Dominic outlets from Grand Metropolitan two years ago, is the leading
retailer with 1,600 shops and a 10 per cent share of the take-home drinks
market.
The merger of Victoria Wine and Augustus Barnett would give Allied an 8.6
per cent market share, well ahead of other specialists such as Oddbins and
Cellar 5 with shares of under 2 per cent.
It would increase sales opportunities for its spirits and beer brands,
improve its purchasing power and enable it to compete more effectively
against the grocery multiples.
The merged chain would be particularly strong in Scotland, where it would
have 330 shops.
Bass is expected to secure a supply agreement for its beers as part of the
deal.
The take-home trade is now one of the fastest-growing sectors of the beer
market, accelerated by the focus on value for money during the recession and
the decline in numbers of younger pub-goers. It is expected to increase its
20 per cent share of total beer sales to 30 per cent by the end of the
decade.
Specialist off-licences have encountered aggressive competition in recent
years from supermarkets, led by J Sainsbury and Tesco, each of which has
raised market share above 9 per cent.
According to Verdict, the market researcher, food retailers - helped by
Sunday opening and evening trading - have captured about half the Pounds 6bn
market for take-home drinks.
The specialist off-licences have been hitting back, however. Victoria Wine
recorded sales growth of 6 per cent last year by providing a greater range
of drinks brands, and by focusing on customer research and service. Augustus
Barnett has been relocating to larger premises.
</TEXT>
