<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BBC2 begins a series, Architecture Of The Imagination (9.30) which promises
to 'explore the deeper meaning of everyday architectural surroundings',
starting with the door. Other programmes will deal with the stairway, the
window, the bridge and the tower, which, we are told, will be analysed via
film clips, contemporary images and psychological revelations. For years
Friday was the night to stay in and watch movies. Often there was an
embarrassment of choice, with several good offers overlapping. And now? BBC1
screens a 1988 flop called She's Having A Baby (10.20) described by the
leading American movie guide as a comedy drama which 'grows monotonous after
a while'. BBC2 offers Fritz Lang's 1948 pot boiler The Secret Beyond The
Door about an heiress who marries a millionaire and suspects she may become
his victim. James Agee said: 'It's a hopeless job and a worthless movie'
(11.20). Channel 4 goes even further back to dig out a Boris Karloff horror
movie from 1936: The Walking Dead(12.05). Sounds like a night when you pays
your money and goes out to dinner.
