<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 93 / Mercury prompts price war in mobile phones
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE long-awaited mobile telephone price war came closer yesterday with the
unveiling of tariffs by Mercury One-2-One, the new cellular mobile network
due to be launched in the M25 area soon.
One-2-One, a joint venture between Cable &amp; Wireless, Mercury's parent, and
US West, will charge only two thirds of the price levied by existing
operators for peak-rate calls made from phones on its new digital network.
The discount on charges for calls to phones on the One-2-One network is
likely to be still larger, and initial connection charges will also be
significantly lower.
One-2-One will charge 16p a minute for calls from its mobile phones at peak
rate, with an initial connection charge for business subscribers of Pounds
20 and a monthly subscription of Pounds 20.
Vodafone, the leading mobile operator, charges 25p a minute at peak rate for
its existing analogue business service, which has national coverage. The
initial charge is Pounds 50 and the monthly charge Pounds 25.
Those charges already represent a significant reduction from a pre-June
Vodafone tariff of 33p a minute for calls in the M25 area. The price cut was
in anticipation of One-2-One's tariffs.
Vodafone is launching its own 'MetroDigital' local digital service this
autumn. Its tariffs will be lower than those for the existing network, but
with a Pounds 50 connection charge and a 20p per minute peak-rate tariff it
will still be more expensive than One-2-One.
Cellnet, the other operator, has yet to announce revised tariffs, but
indicated last week that reductions were on the way.
One-2-One has nearly completed its customer trials and the launch of its
network is imminent. It plans to expand beyond the M25 to cover about 13m
people in the south-east by the middle of next year.
Handsets for use on the One-2-One network will retail for between Pounds 250
and Pounds 300, compared with about Pounds 399 for handsets compatible with
the MetroDigital network.
One-2-One will offer a special tariff for low users, who will have a reduced
monthly subscription of Pounds 12.50 but pay 25p a minute for peak-rate
calls.
Facilities with the One-2-One service include itemised billing, call
barring, call waiting, call divert, and voice mail.
Among new cost-control features is a monthly call limit allowing customers -
or their managers - to set a ceiling on permitted expenditure.
</TEXT>
