<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 93 / Councils cannot 'opt in' to review
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PLANS TO allow councils to 'opt in' to the review of local government in
England have been vetoed by Mr John Major, Alison Smith writes.
The proposal from Mr John Gummer, environment secretary, to allow councils
to vote in favour of inclusion in the review, was among suggestions for
overhauling the reorganisation of local government.
Today's Local Government Chronicle says the prime minister rejected the idea
of making the review voluntary last week. An announcement on the revision is
not now expected until September.
Mr Major's main reason, it says, was that making later stages of the review
optional would encourage Scottish and Welsh councils to try to avoid being
reviewed. Legislation on Scottish and Welsh local government is due to come
forward in November.
The environment department wants to speed up the review so that it does not
last the scheduled three more years.
</TEXT>
