<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 93 / Government aims to slam door on invasions of privacy: Green
paper draws on European code - Lengthy court battles predicted / Public
interest to be a defence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE IS no right to privacy in English or Scots law, as former cabinet
ministers, stars of television's ''Allo 'Allo' and members of the royal
family can testify.
The green paper on infringement of privacy published yesterday canvasses the
idea of a new civil action giving individuals the right to sue anyone for
damages who causes them distress by invading their privacy.
Three years ago a committee chaired by Sir David Calcutt QC concluded that
there was no overwhelming case for introducing such a cause of action.
It considered, largely on principle and the availability of other options
for protecting privacy, that stronger self-regulation by the press with the
introduction of criminal offences to cover three forms of physical intrusion
would suffice.
Asked two years later to consider whether self-regulation had worked, Sir
David concluded that it had not and that the government should consider a
new civil action for infringement of privacy.
Yet in the intervening years there was no obvious increase in public concern
about privacy.
Between January 1991 and July 1992 the Press Complaints Commission received
211 complaints on privacy including those concerning harassment and
intrusion into grief or shock. Of those 109 were admissible and few went to
full adjudication.
The Broadcasting Complaints Commission receives only one or two cases a year
relating to privacy.
Even the green paper acknowledges that if a new civil action were created
the total volume of cases reaching the courts under a general privacy law
'would probably be in the hundreds rather than the thousands'.
The protections of privacy which Calcutt considered sufficient in 1990 are
still in place. Seclusion can be protected by trespass and nuisance laws.
Personal information can be protected by the laws of breach of confidence,
copyright and contract, and private life by laws on defamation and malicious
falsehood.
The criminal law gives some protection from harassment and physical
intrusions, for example under the Interception of Communications Act. In
family life domestic violence laws protect spouses and partners from
molestation.
In recommending the creation of a civil action for infringement of privacy
the government appears to have been swayed as much as anything by the
express protection accorded to privacy in most other European countries and
by the European Convention on Human Rights, which provides that 'everyone
has the right to respect for his private and family life, his home and his
correspondence'.
The French civil code provides that every person has the right to respect
for his private life. The right applies only to individuals and not
companies, but covers not only invasions of privacy by the press but also by
banks, insurance companies, credit agencies and central and local
government. French courts can award damages and make orders preventing
publication of material which breaches the right of privacy.
In Germany the civil code provides a right of action for damages against a
person who 'wilfully or negligently injures the life, body, health, freedom,
property or other right of another, contrary to the law . . .'
In the US most states have statutes or a body of case law protecting
privacy, including both criminal offences and civil actions. In Canada
several provinces have privacy acts making wilful violation of privacy
actionable.
The green paper proposes the creation of a civil cause of action in England,
Wales and Scotland for individuals in respect of conduct which constitutes
an infringement of privacy causing substantial distress, provided that 'such
distress would also have been suffered by a person of ordinary sensibilities
in the circumstances of the complainant'.
Privacy would cover a person's health, personal communications and family
and personal relationships and a right to be free from harassment and
molestation.
The green paper asks whether publication of inaccurate or misleading
information or of information 'putting a person in a false light' should be
included as a category, and whether it would be appropriate for legislation
to include 'appropriation of a person's identity'.
The government does not intend to make someone who infringes another's
privacy strictly liable. It proposes that a defendant be liable only if the
infringement was intentional, reckless or negligent.
The green paper proposes several defences: consent, both express and
implied; absolute or qualified privilege equivalent to that in defamation
cases; and a public-interest defence. It also canvasses the idea that there
should be a defence of necessary protection, such as the employment of a
private investigator to check on errant spouses or employees suspected of
industrial espionage.
The government is also seeking comments on whether it should be a defence
that the matters in issue were the subject of public record or took place in
public.
The paper proposes that plaintiffs should be able to obtain an injunction
preventing publication of material which would result in an infringement of
privacy. The usual maximum level of damages would be Pounds 10,000, with
awards of up to Pounds 25,000 in exceptional cases. As with defamation there
would be no legal aid available.
The government is seeking comments by mid-October.
Infringement of Privacy. Consultation Paper July 1993. Available from the
Lord Chancellor's Department or the Scottish Office.
</TEXT>
