FT  30 JUL 93 / Welcome for rules which will 'drag tabloids out of gutter'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM KING and RACHEL JOHNSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MS CLARE Short, the MP whose complaint to the Press Complaints Commission
was upheld in 1991 after the News of the World published a photograph of her
in her nightdress, welcomed the proposals and said the press would not have
'trawled' through her private life had they been law. 'It will drag the
tabloid press out of the gutter,' she said.
Her sentiments were typical of people who have had run-ins with the press
and pursued their grievances through existing arrangements.
Mrs Linda Townley is suing Today newspaper for malicious falsehood after it
alleged in 1989 that she stole letters from Princess Anne while in her
employment. Mrs Townley said she probably would have used the proposed
privacy law if it had existed.
Mrs Diane Simpson, a researcher, was photographed talking to Mr Peter
Sutcliffe, the Yorkshire Ripper, by someone who gained access to Broadmoor
hospital by subterfuge.
She said the proposed legislation would have protected patients. But she
agreed that intrusions into privacy could sometimes be in the public
interest.
Others felt that the proposals - which do not provide for legal aid - did
not offer enough protection.
Ms Mona Alghussein, then known as Mrs Mona Bauwens, became the subject of
press interest because of gifts she made to Mr David Mellor, the former
heritage secretary.
She said she was more concerned about accuracy than privacy, 'though there
were certain aspects of my private life that I didn't think were anyone's
interest'. The proposed legislation was no use without legal aid, she said.
