<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 93 / Tougher regulation of BT satellite business urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SATELLITE business of British Telecommunications would be subject to
more detailed regulation under proposals published yesterday by Oftel, the
telecommunications regulator.
Under Oftel's plans, BT would have to publish a financial statement covering
the activities of the division, which is responsible for selling satellite
capacity to rival operators.
BT would be barred from seeking investment contributions from other
operators.
The move marks a further extension of regulatory pressure by Oftel, coming
after a series of recent proposals to make the company more open to its
competitors.
The review of existing arrangements between BT and other companies offering
satellite links concerns the provision of satellite capacity with Intelsat
and Eutelsat - satellites funded and operated by consortia of state
telecommunications companies.
Three years ago BT established a 'signatory affairs office' to give
independent satellite service operators access to capacity.
Mr Don Cruickshank, Oftel director-general, said: 'The proposed changes will
help create the right conditions for greater competition in the UK satellite
service market, which will mean a wider range of innovative and keenly
priced services being made available to customers.'
He said the new arrangements would give competitors 'confidence' in the
signatory affairs office, 'although as the satellite consortia move towards
direct access for capacity the role of the SAO will naturally diminish'.
BT welcomed the plans but said it needed to consider the implications of
some of the regulatory proposals.
</TEXT>
