<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 93 / Talks prompted Swan Hunter to lift its offer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NAO report seeks to explain one of the most puzzling episodes in modern
defence procurement history - how two shipyards, both UK-based, could come
up with bids for the same vessel which were Pounds 71m apart.
The report discloses that the MoD 'reminded' Swan Hunter early this year
that it would consider giving it the helicopter carrier order if it were
taken over by a more financially secure company, able to provide the
required guarantee of due performance.
At that time Swans was negotiating a takeover by GEC. Ironically, it was
advice from GEC-Marconi, which Swans concurred with and the MoD assessed as
realistic, which added Pounds 12.2m for increased overheads to Swans final
bid. While VSEL's bid dropped, from Pounds 165m to Pounds 139.5m, Swan's
rose from Pounds 174.5m to Pounds 210.6m.
The report says that the MoD's evaluation of the two initial bids, implied
lower overhead rates for both than would have been expected. Nevertheless
the department concluded that 'the tendered prices could be considered to be
realistic'.
Neither bid was fully technically compliant at that stage. No 'bottom-line'
comparison of the merits of the two bids was made.
The department's main financial analysis of the reasonableness of the best
and final offer bids was limited to a subjective review. Because of the
compressed timescale it relied on a 'senior management brainstorm' to
identify key risks.
It concluded the lower VSEL bid represented an acceptable price.
Swan Hunter's bid, MoD technical experts concluded in a detailed review
after the contract award, was 'realistic but unaffordable'.
</TEXT>
