<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 93 / 'Quangoland' of Wales warned
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN REDWOOD, the Welsh secretary, warned chairmen of Welsh quangos
yesterday that the public expected national boards to maintain the 'highest
standards of probity and fairness'. He said: 'I look to all the chairmen to
lead, by insisting on the highest standards of conduct.'
He said if things did go wrong 'the public likes an early apology from the
board and is entitled to expect that disciplinary action will be taken if
necessary'.
Mr Redwood told chairmen of Welsh non-departmental public bodies that there
were limits to the number of functions which could best be handled by
quangos - quasi-autonomous non-governmental bodies.
He added: 'Many services require either the direct political control and
accountability of local government or the Welsh Office. I do not want
Quangoland to grow too fat on functions transferred from local government.'
His comments come a few weeks after the publication of a highly critical
report by the Commons public accounts committee about the internal
management of the Welsh Development Agency.
The investigation followed concerns raised by the National Audit Office
about the WDA's 1991-92 accounts.
In a report published today, the audit office condemns the way in which
another quango, the Development Board for Rural Wales, allocated housing
under a secret set of rules separate to those which were made public.
It says the board's own housing officer was involved in allocating houses to
himself and his former wife when neither was eligible under the published
rules.
</TEXT>
