<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 93 / Voters exact revenge for 'betrayal': Philip Stephens
explains the swing from the Tories in Christchurch
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT WAS lost before it started. The seething discontent which cost Mr John
Major his party's 15th-safest seat in the early hours of this morning was
obvious from the outset of the Christchurch by-election campaign.
Two thirds of the electors of the sleepy seaside constituency in east Dorset
voted Conservative at the general election only 15 months ago.
This week these once-loyal footsoldiers of southern Toryism were set on one
thing above all else - to exact revenge on a government that had broken its
promises.
The word heard most frequently on the doorsteps of the neat suburban
bungalows and the grander middle-class villas strung across the constituency
was 'betrayal'.
The prime minister had promised them that their support on April 9 1992
would bring economic recovery on April 10. Instead the recession had dragged
for another year. Even now they were suspicious of the evidence that the
upturn is at last a reality.
They had been told that Mr Major, like his predecessor, would cut their
taxes. Instead he had put them up - and done so in a way that which
penalised those on modest if not low incomes.
Pace Mr Norman Lamont, the imposition of value added tax on domestic heating
may yet be destined to find a place in the history books as one of the
biggest political blunders of modern times.
Those two betrayals might not have been enough of themselves to overturn the
23,000 majority bequeathed by the charming individualist, the late Robert
Adley.
But overlaying them was widespread disaffection at all the government's
policies. Mr Major was perceived as weak, his party as divided and
self-indulgent. Rising crime rates have infuriated a population with more
than its fair share of the vulnerable elderly.
Even Mr Major's promise of another burst of privatisation and deregulation
raised hackles. The voters of Christchurch do not want their local stores
driven out of business by Sunday-opening hypermarkets, their sub-post
offices sacrificed on the altar of free-market efficiency, their rail
services privatised.
The message from ministers this morning will be that this was a mid-term
protest. Governments rarely win by-elections - and never at the tail-end of
a recession.
Downing Street has already rehearsed its response. Ministers will insist
that the outcome reflected the past rather than the future. Mr Major has put
behind him the civil war over Maastricht which so gravely damaged his
political authority. The sunlit uplands of economic recovery beckon.
To an extent they are right. Few expect Mrs Diana Maddock, the studiously
dull Liberal Democrat MP, to hold the seat beyond the next general election.
Look, after all, at what happened to the victors in the last parliament of
Eastbourne, Ribble Valley, and Kincardine and Deeside.
There were special circumstances also. The peculiar make-up of the
constituency - about a third of the population are above pensionable age -
proved particularly fertile ground for opposition 'scare stories' about
plans for new NHS prescription charges and hotel fees for hospital stays.
The retired and near-retired of Christchurch - not rich but sufficiently
well-off not to qualify for state benefits - will suffer more than most the
impact of high domestic fuel charges.
But Mr Major should beware of believing his own excuses. The campaign in
Christchurch has shown how detached the government has become from its own
traditional supporters among the lower middle classes.
The prime minister is perceived as weak and ineffective even by paid-up
members of his own party. These greying classes are represent one of the
most powerful interest groups in the southern, and particularly
south-western, English constituencies that the Conservatives must win to
remain in government.
In the county council elections and in the Newbury by-election in May, and
again yesterday, they defected to the Liberal Democrats in huge numbers.
Mr Paddy Ashdown's party remains one of local rather than national politics.
But it is beginning to put down roots across a swathe of territory vital to
the Conservatives. If he is to survive, Mr Major will have to listen to the
electors of Christchurch.
</TEXT>
