<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 93 / Councils cannot 'opt in' to review
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PLANS to allow councils to 'opt in' to the review of local government in
England have been vetoed by Mr John Major.
The proposal from Mr John Gummer, environment secretary, to allow councils
to vote in favour of being included in the review, was among suggestions for
overhauling the re-organisation of local government to the commission
chaired by Sir John Banham.
Today's edition of the Local Government Chronicle says the prime minister
had rejected the idea of making the review voluntary at a meeting with Mr
Gummer last week. An announcement on the revision of the review is not now
expected until September.
Mr Major's main reason, it says, was that putting the later tranches of the
review on an optional basis would encourage Scottish and Welsh councils to
try to avoid being reviewed.
Legislation on Scottish and Welsh local government is due to come forward in
the new parliamentary session which starts in November.
If the English review had become voluntary, ministers would also have faced
considerable political embarrassment in seeming to show such a lack of
confidence in a policy intended to be a vote-winner.
The Tory election manifesto pledged that a commission would examine 'area by
area' the structure of local government in England. The aim was to deliver a
council structure that would be popular with local communities and give back
self-governance to cities such as Bristol and Leicester.
So far, however, the commission has aroused controversy in each of the four
areas for which it has announced its proposals.
Even without the option of setting proportions of local councils in any one
area which would have to vote in favour of the review to be included in it,
there is still considerable scope for changing the form of the next four
tranches of the commission's work by altering its policy guidance.
Significant changes that seem likely are setting new ways of assessing cost
effectiveness and measuring local community identity.
</TEXT>
