<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 93 / US markets shrug off GDP figures: Economy grew more slowly
than expected in quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US economy grew far more sluggishly in the second quarter than
economists had expected, but the financial markets found a silver lining to
the superficially gloomy report.
The Commerce Department said US gross domestic product grew at an annual
rate of only 1.6 per cent last quarter, after the weak 0.7 per cent growth
of the opening period.
Mr Ron Brown, commerce secretary, said there were encouraging signs in the
report, but 'while we are clearly out of a recession, these figures reflect
anaemic growth that will not produce the jobs we need'.
The Commerce Department said strong rises in personal spending, business
investment and exports were offset by a sharp slowdown in inventory building
by businesses, which subtracted Dollars 25.3bn (Pounds 16.9bn) from growth
in the second quarter, after adding Dollars 23.7bn in the first quarter.
Personal consumption rose at an annual rate of 3.8 per cent in the second
period, led by purchases of durable goods, while non-residential fixed
investment rose at 13.3 per cent and exports at 6.7 per cent.
This left real final sales, which exclude the inventory effect, growing at
an annual rate of 3.7 per cent, after contracting at a rate of 1.2 per cent
in the first quarter.
'If you look at the guts of the report, it tells you the economy is doing
fine,' said Mr Bill Dudley, an economist with Goldman Sachs.
'The combination of final sales growth at 3.7 per cent and the slowdown in
inventory growth is a reason to be less worried about a very sluggish
number,' added Mr Jason Benderly, of Benderly Economic Associates, a
Colorado research company.
This interpretation of the figures sent bond prices up sharply yesterday,
pushing yields to record lows, while share prices soared. At the close the
Dow Jones industrial average was up 13.97 at 3,567.42.
The weak GDP figure came only a week after Mr Alan Greenspan, chairman of
the Federal Reserve, had confidently predicted second quarter growth would
reach 2.5-3 per cent. Members of Congress were last week perturbed by Mr
Greenspan's signal that the next move for US rates was likely to be upwards.
However, economists said the weak overall growth figure seemed likely to
delay plans to raise rates.
</TEXT>
