<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 93 / Bosnians weigh up plan for union of republics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL mediators in Geneva yesterday proposed a union of three
Bosnian republics, in an attempt to bridge the gap between the warring
parties about the future of the region.
The plan, presented by Lord Owen and Mr Thorvald Stoltenberg, seeks to
satisfy Serb and Croat demands for partition of Bosnia on ethnic lines as
well as the Moslem aim of creating a federal republic, a United Nations
official said.
Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic welcomed the plan and said he could
accept it with 'only minor changes' since it was 'pretty close' to the
Serb-Croat proposal for ethnic mini-states.
Bosnia's Moslem President Alija Izetbegovic last night consulted the Bosnian
collective leadership after seeking revisions in the plan, which goes
against all his calls for a more closely knit federation. But members of the
collective leadership were divided on the plan and will meet again today to
try to agree a united position.
Bosnian Prime Minister Mile Akmadzic predicted that all three Bosnian
factions, including the Moslem-led government, would accept the plan. Mr
Akmadzic, a Croat, said: 'I am really convinced that all three sides,
including the presidency. . . will agree on the new constitutional
arrangement.'
Diplomats said the mediators' proposal would give the Bosnian central
government control over foreign policy but few other powers.
A meeting of all six parties at the Geneva talks is expected later today. A
UN official said the participants at Geneva were talking 'seriously,
courteously and constructively'.
Bosnian leaders yesterday agreed on a ceasefire in the 16-month war. Mr
Izetbegovic, Mr Karadzic and the Bosnian Croat leader, Mr Mate Boban,
interrupted a session of talks to issue the ceasefire order to their
military commanders, said UN spokesman John Mills.
Despite the order to implement the accord immediately, there was no sign in
Bosnia that any ceasefire would hold. Previous truces have collapsed almost
immediately.
In Washington, Mr Francois Leotard, the French defence minister, said the
western allies with troops in Bosnia would not tolerate further attacks on
UN troops and were prepared to launch air strikes quickly if they continued.
</TEXT>
