<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 93 / London Stock Exchange: BAT nerves
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO, CHRISTOPHER PRICE and CHRISTINE BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Worries about the cigarette price war in the US overhung international
trading group BAT Industries, which reported interim figures in line with
market expectations.
Profits were up 35 per cent to Pounds 906m and the dividend was raised by 8
per cent, which initially inspired demand for the stock, sending it forward
9 to 459p. However, a sombre analysts' meeting at which the company focused
on the stiff competition in the US cigarette market saw initial enthusiasm
wane and the shares finished a net 4 off at 446p after volume of 7m, well
above usual trading levels.
Mr Andrew Mitchell at Smith New Court said: 'Although a cloud remains over
the US tobacco side, the dividend yield remains a key attraction in the long
term.'
Rumours of a big share placing, together with the sale of a large chunk of
directors' equity holdings, took the shine off Taunton Cider, although the
stock later rallied. The shares closed just a penny off at 204p after hefty
turnover of 8.5m. The directors and family interests sold 1.6m shares at
197p. A large line of stock was said to have been placed at 201p.
The Greenalls bid for JA Devenish was declared unconditional, coinciding
with Schroder selling the rump of stock issued for those shareholders who
took the cash alternative. These shares were bought at 350p and placed in
the market, with total turnover hitting 10m. Greenalls closed 2 easier at
353p. Devenish finished 9 ahead at 368p.
Hotel group Stakis placed 18m new shares in the market through its broker
Smith New Court as part of a deal to buy a hotel in York, UK, for Pounds
5.85m. Smith placed the shares at 53.25p with a variety of institutions.
Stakis slipped a penny to 55p.
A large seller in Wembley left the shares 2 down at 11 1/2 p after turnover
of 1.4m.
Results from BT failed to excite investors, with worries over increased
competition and regulatory concerns overshadowing events. The shares faded
to close 1 1/2 off at 417 1/2 p.
Reuters Holdings gave up 5 to 1439p in spite of a buy note from NatWest
Securities as sellers continued to nibble away at gains made on the recent
share buy-back plan.
Aero-engine manufacturer Rolls-Royce eased 3 1/2 to 138 1/2 p, with overseas
holders believed to have been among the chief sellers. Volume at the close
was 3.8m shares.
Shares in Channel tunnel operator Eurotunnel added 10 at 444p, following
Tuesday's agreement between the company and TransManche Link, the consortium
constructing the tunnel. National Express ended 9 up at 249p after a stake
of around 8 per cent changed hands.
Profit-taking after its recent run left British Aerospace 6 lighter at 416p.
A slight shortage of stock and a reported recommendation from Strauss
Turnbull boosted Smiths Industries, which rose 6 to 357p. The recent
positive stance from Panmure Gordon continued to boost Vosper Thornycroft
and the shares advanced a further 14 to 641p.
Among the motor stocks, T. Cowie firmed 4 1/2 to 248p on the prospect of
good August car sales.
Profit-takers moved into Pearson after the progress achieved on the previous
day on the back of plans to spin off two parts of its operations. The shares
retreated 10 to 457p.
Fortunes moved in the opposite direction for Mirror Group Newspapers, which
enjoyed a rally to recover more of the ground lost in the tabloid price war.
At 154p, the stock added 5.
Good results from a US rival of lubricants group Burmah Castrol led to
demand for the stock. The shares strengthened 15 to 731p, with sentiment
boosted by news that it was raising its stake in Castrol India to 51 per
cent from a previous 40 per cent. Shell Transport put on 4 at 632p in volume
of 2.4m, ahead of next week's figures.
Turnover in British Gas rose to 11m as the shares continued their recent
recovery, gaining 7 at 306p. There was speculation that further job cuts may
be announced if the UK Monopolies and Mergers Commission recommends a
restructuring of the business. A summary of the report is expected on August
17. Hopes of a recovery in oil prices boosted Enterprise Oil, which rose 10
to 455p.
In the banking sector, hopes that TSB would soon announce the sale of Hill
Samuel, its merchant banking subsidiary, helped the shares improve 5 to
201p, in trade of 4.7m.
Insurance and financial services group Lloyds Abbey Life climbed 11 to 418p
after a 7.3 per cent increase in profits.
The agreement between Eurotunnel and TML had a mixed effect on building
shares. Costain edged up a penny to 37p, while Taylor Woodrow closed at its
starting level of 114p after having reached a high of 116p. George Wimpey
receded 6 to 169p after profit-takers took the shine off the rise made on
the previous day on the Channel tunnel agreement.
Good results from paper and packaging group David. S Smith attracted
investor support and the stock appreciated 10 to 380p.
Nervousness ahead of ICI's results, due today, saw the shares retreat 9 to
650p. Its former drugs business, Zeneca, also reporting today, gave up 4 to
622p.
Television stocks mustered a firm performance, with Scottish TV adding 4 at
513p, Central Independent TV moving forward 5 to 1970p and Grampian TV
increasing by 2 to 230p.
Business services company Danka Business closed 8 ahead at 230p after an
improvement in first-quarter profits.
Shares in Goode Durrant brushed aside a full-year loss of Pounds 15.3m and
improved 7 to 93p, helped by a confident statement on the future outlook for
the company.
</TEXT>
