<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Merck fall puts check on
advance by Dow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
ENCOURAGING economic news failed to lift US stock markets yesterday as
declines in several big stocks, including Du Pont and Merck, left share
prices lower at the close, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the end of a volatile day's trading the Dow Jones Industrial Average was
down 12.01 at 3,553.45. The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 slipped
1.05 to 447.19, although in the over-the-counter market the Nasdaq composite
rose 4.59 to 705.59. Trading volume on the New York SE totalled 273m shares.
The day's economic news was broadly positive. The Commerce Department
announced a 3.8 per cent climb in June durable goods orders, an increase
three times larger than analysts had forecast. The figures, however, came
with a catch.
The big increase was due primarily to a jump in orders for commercial
aircraft, a traditionally volatile component. Without the aircraft orders,
the overall increase was just 0.3 per cent. Even so, analysts said that they
were still relieved to see that orders were up in June.
The news failed to lift market sentiment or prices, which tumbled at the
opening. Although some investors continued to take profits following recent
record highs for the Dow, the bulk of the decline was attributable to a
handful of leading stocks.
Merck led the way, falling almost Dollars 2 in early trading after the big
drugs group announced a Dollars 6bn acquisition of Medco Containment
Services, which will be funded through a new equity issue and debt
financing. Merck recovered some of its loss later in the day, and at the
close the stock was down Dollars 1 3/8 at Dollars 30 3/4 after volume of
12.47m shares. Medco, traded on the Nasdaq market, jumped Dollars 4 3/8 to
Dollars 34 1/8 .
Du Pont fell Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 47 1/4 after the company disappointed
the markets with second-quarter earnings of 76 cents a share, well below the
84 cents expected by analysts.
Chrysler dropped Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars 42 5/8 in turnover of 9.5m shares,
even though the car maker unveiled strong second-quarter net income of
Dollars 685m, which included one-off gains worth Dollars 110m from the sale
of stock and a plastics unit. The decline may have been a natural correction
following recent big gains in Chrysler's share price.
In the same sector, Ford Motor climbed Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 52 in volume
of 2.1m shares on news of an impressive improvement in second-quarter
earnings. General Motors' class E shares, which represent the company's EDS
unit, advanced Dollars 2 to Dollars 28 1/8 after the company, which
announced as-expected profits yesterday, said it expected double-digit
percentage revenue growth in 1993.
Eastman Kodak moved ahead Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 52 3/8 after reporting
second-quarter net income of Dollars 1.13 a share, up from Dollars 1.11 a
year earlier, even after a special charge.
Canada
TORONTO continued to climb in moderate trading. The TSE 300 index finished
11.5 higher at 3,923.1 and rises led declines by 403 to 301 after volume of
52m shares valued at CDollars 569.5m.
Among the sub-indices, nine of the 14 gained ground. Golds recorded the
day's biggest change, rising 1.13 per cent.
</TEXT>
